    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-06-30T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-06-30T10:00:00-05:00" n="135"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d135">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/5392: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland (<persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_WHR1" type="from">Wilson</persName>) to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-06-30T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 30, 1932—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 30—1:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>99. Meeting of Nineteen at 3 tomorrow, Assembly at 5:30. <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_LS1">Lester</persName>, Irish representative, has
                    just spoken to me saying that some of the smaller powers were anxious to insert
                    in the President’s declaration <pb facs="0221" n="123" xml:id="pg_123"/> to the
                    Assembly a warning to Japan that recognition of the Manchurian Government would
                    be considered by the League members as contrary to the undertaking not to
                    prejudice the situation pending the <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_LERB1"
                        >Lytton</persName> report. He suggested that it would be of great importance
                    if the view of the United States as to the advisability of such a step could be
                    received.</p>
                <p>In view of the shortness of time I told him that it was unlikely that you could
                    get an answer back. If you care to have any advice given I suggest that I do it
                    personally through <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_DSE1"
                    >Drummond</persName>.</p>
                <p>In this connection <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_DSE1">Drummond</persName> has
                    informed <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_DCM1">Davis</persName> that <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_DSE1">Drummond</persName> considers that such action
                    would be dangerous and resented in Japan as an interference with their foreign
                    policy and perhaps drive them to more important action than they were
                    contemplating.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_WHR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
